<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-27T23:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-27T23:36:00-05:00" n="940" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d940">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/13610.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Brazilian Minister</gloss> to
                                Mexico to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-27T22:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 27, 1914, 10 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>191. My October 14, 10 p.m., No. 187. Notwithstanding that the Convention
                            had authorized Carranza to grant the guaranties desired by the
                            Department, I have just received a note from the Acting Secretary for
                            Foreign Affairs in which, after having enumerated the Department’s
                                requests,<note n="67" xml:id="d940fn67">As conveyed by the Brazilian
                                Minister in his note of October 8 embodying the Department’s
                                telegram No. 281 of October 7, 5 p.m.</note> he says:</p>
                        <p>[Text of part of the note; see the complete text in the next paper.]
                            Translation of the note will follow in the mail tomorrow.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cardoso de Oliveira</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>